node.text: Wolves deep in #DenaliNationalPark, Alaska. Leading their offspring to new hunting grounds, the Iron Creek pack’s breeding pair breaks trail through fresh snow with the female leading. I watched this pack over the course of 3 days as they devoured a Moose and then was lucky enough to catch them as they left the kill site crossing this large unbroken field of snow. Much of the rest of the park had less snow from a warm dry winter and it was harder to see the wolves in the patchy brown and green of the trees. This shot was the result of a little luck, but mostly relentless searching for the right pack in the right photo conditions. The payoff was worth the time put in!  Shot on assignment for @natgeo #wolves #alaska

One of my favorite photos from #Svaneti, Georgia!  Lit-up by burning birch torches in the shadows of 13th century towers, villagers in Mulakhi pour alcohol on the graves of relatives in a ceremony/festival called Lamproba (Lamps Festival). The festival pre-dates the arrival of Christianity and is one of the oldest preserved traditions in the region of its kind.  Ive heard two stories of its meaning:  One says the lamps were to warm the souls of the dead, another story said it was a pagan ritual asking the deities for healthy crops and good weather.  #Sakartvelo for @natgeo

The villages of Ushguli in #Svaneti (Georgia) are even more dramatic when the snows fall!  Completely cut off from the outside world on days like this, these UNESCO world heritage sites look as they must have when these defensive towers were built in the 13th Century.  An unpublished photo from an assignment for @natgeo.

Missing the mountains and mysteries of #Svaneti.  So many beautiful rituals to have witnessed.  Lighting candles in the Lagurka church in Kala, #Sakartvelo.  Unpublished image from a story for @natgeo magazine.

At the Quiricoba Festival in Kala, #Svanetia (in the country of Georgia), young men compete to lift a 300+ lb stone, with the goal of throwing it over their head to land behind them.  Most cannot get the stone off the ground.  Shot on assignment for @NatGeo. #StrongMan Contest #Sakartvelo #DinosaurEgg?

An older image of mine that feels more timely every year.  I wrote a short piece about this assignment for @harpersmagazine called “a temporary apocalypse” talking about the feeling of dropping into emergency zones like big wildfires.  But now all these temporary apocalypses seem to be merging into one big one that never end... #wearetheasteroid (From the Yorba Linda-Corona fire of 2008)

#Sponsored by @GeorgiaTravel // A long time ago, with my first camera, I was lucky enough to stumble into the country of Georgia and it changed my life.  It was waaaay off the beaten path, and #Svanetia, an isolated region surrounded by 17,000 ft peaks, where villages are still made up of clusters of 13th Century defensive towers, was like a dream made real.  It is still a place that feels completely out of time with hikes among the clouds for the adventurous traveller.  To see more of this stunning country follow #GeorgiaTravelMoments

From the Olympic Peninsula, on the Washington coast. To continue from my last post, these are not shot with a DSLR, they are from a few days of testing the #64MPQuadCameraXpert.  This phone camera could do long exposures and keep a low ISO (slide 1 and yesterday's post). It also had a super wide setting which Im always missing on the expensive phone thats usually in my pocket (slide 2). The range of color made me shake my head in disbelief because it was often more than my eye could see (slide 3). And the detail I could get when zooming in on a 64MP image macro shot (slide 4-5) was beyond anything I have ever seen a cell phone make.  When we ran into things the camera couldn't do I worked with the tech team on site and they debugged the programming on the device in real time.  It was a pretty amazing experience and Im excited to help launch the phone today in India!  #realmeXT #realme #DareToLeap #sponsored @realmeindia @realmeglobal

I always love experimenting with new technology, and recently had the opportunity to test one of the first 64MP mobile camera phones, and collaborate with the tech team behind it to help fine tune the features and capabilities.  Most of the world cant afford $1000+ cell phone cameras, so working to help develop and refine a device thats a fraction of the price of the phones most of us carry around felt really good. The phone isn't available in America yet, but billions of people in China, India, Europe and SouthEast Asia can get their hands on it soon.  In this photo Im testing its night shot capabilities on the Washington Coast!  The detail for a low light shot was ridiculous!!! Swipe left to see how sharp a long exposure cell phone night shot can be!  #64MPQuadCameraXpert @realmeglobal @realmeindia #realme #DareToLeap #realmeXT #sponsored
